I watch a single leaf detach, caught in a spiral of air, tumbling down past the glass. It’s brown and curled, a perfect little cup. It lands on the grass with a soft thud I can almost hear through the window. It’s done. The season is moving on. And I’m still here, thinking about numbers and palindromes and the truth of 2. The leaf doesn’t care. The wind doesn’t care. Only I care. And even I, I’m not sure how much.

I close my eyes and listen to the wind. It’s a good sound. A clean sound. It’s the sound of the world changing, and me, sitting here, watching it happen. One thought growing out of the last. The leaf falling. The wind blowing. The mind thinking. All part of the same process. All part of the same truth.


